<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What regions produce the best Pinot Noir under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oregon's Willamette Valley, California's Central Coast, and Chile's Casablanca Valley consistently offer exceptional value for Pinot Noir under $20. These regions benefit from ideal cool-climate conditions that allow Pinot Noir to ripen slowly while maintaining natural acidity. New Zealand's Central Otago and France's Languedoc also produce surprisingly elegant bottles in this price range, though availability may be more limited.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I tell if a $15 Pinot Noir is actually good quality?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for wines with clear varietal character - bright red fruit aromas like cherry and raspberry, balanced acidity, and silky tannins rather than harsh astringency. Quality indicators include single-vineyard designations, specific appellations (not just "California"), and producers with established reputations. Avoid bottles with excessive oak flavors or overly jammy fruit, which often mask poor winemaking in budget wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Pinot Noir under $20 good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, affordable Pinot Noir is excellent for beginners because it typically offers approachable fruit flavors without overwhelming tannins or alcohol heat. The lighter body and bright acidity make it food-friendly and easy to drink. Budget Pinot Noir also teaches beginners to appreciate subtle differences between regions and producers without the pressure of expensive bottles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between a $12 and $18 Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The $18 bottle typically shows more complexity, better balance, and clearer expression of terroir, often from more specific vineyard sites or lower-yielding vines. You'll usually find more nuanced flavors, better integration of oak (if used), and longer finish. The $12 bottle may be perfectly enjoyable but often relies more on blending from multiple sources and may show simpler, more straightforward fruit flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I age budget Pinot Noir or drink it young?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Pinot Noir under $20 is designed to drink within 2-3 years of release and won't significantly improve with extended aging. These wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment and may lose their fresh fruit character if held too long. However, well-made examples from cooler climates can develop pleasant secondary flavors over 3-5 years if stored properly.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What foods pair best with inexpensive Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Budget Pinot Noir's lighter tannins and bright acidity make it incredibly versatile with food, particularly salmon, roasted chicken, mushroom dishes, and pork tenderloin. The wine's moderate alcohol and fresh fruit flavors won't overpower delicate preparations. It's also excellent with charcuterie, soft cheeses like Brie, and vegetarian dishes featuring earthy ingredients like roasted beets or grilled portobello mushrooms.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes when buying cheap Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is choosing wines from overly warm regions where Pinot Noir becomes jammy and loses its elegant character - avoid generic "California" labels from the Central Valley. Don't be swayed by heavily discounted bottles that seem too good to be true, as they may be past their prime. Also avoid wines with excessive oak or alcohol levels above 14.5%, which indicate a heavier style that masks Pinot Noir's natural finesse.</p>
  </div>

